english:
  title: A Memorial Urging Study of the Classics
  author: Yun Seo-jong
  language: eng
  text: |-
    The Book of Changes says: 'When the foolish are instructed in what is right, the sage accomplishes his work.' Heaven bestows upon all beings a nature that is inherently good and without evil. In their beginnings, common people are no different from Yao and Shun. The sage-kings of old were born with the benefit of prenatal instruction, and when yet in swaddling clothes, were guarded by nurses who protected their bodies and arranged their rest and movement with care, instilling in them a reverent and cautious heart. Teachers were appointed to instruct them in virtue and righteousness, restraining excessive desires and preventing harmful sights and sounds. Only upright gentlemen were chosen to accompany them in all their comings and goings, so that whatever they saw was virtuous conduct, whatever they heard was righteous speech. No temptation from the outer world could enter, and their original nature was preserved pure. Their hearts became clear chambers of learning, unobstructed, and thus all could become like Yao and Shun.

    Your servant observes that Your Highness has been studying the Analects for thirteen months now, and each day learns scarcely more than three or four characters, sometimes struggling even with these. Yet Your Highness possesses brilliant and wise abilities granted by Heaven—it is not that you lack capacity for learning. Rather, whenever you sit briefly at your desk, you soon retire within, growing accustomed to the company of favored attendants, your mind drawn to external matters, distant from your studies. Of late, the signs of negligence have become apparent. Before your teachers have even departed, before their instruction has truly been understood, you rise suddenly from your seat, hastily summoning a meal, and withdraw into the inner chambers. How can sacred learning progress? How can your virtuous nature grow bright?

    When the Former King first ascended the throne, he was quick of mind and eager to learn, yet treacherous ministers, scheming to steal the realm, abolished the Classics Lecture and led the Former King astray, nearly overturning our ancestral shrine. When Your Highness took the throne, the great ministers, taking the Former King's fate as a warning, first established the Classics Lecture to encourage sacred learning, hoping that you would become like Yao and Shun. If you grow negligent in your studies, what answer can we give to the ancestral temple? What answer to the common people?

    Now in early autumn came the grain-destroying winds, bringing calamity upon the nation and its people—Heaven's reproach could be no greater. The Book of Hong Fan states: 'When virtue is manifest, gentle winds blow in season; when foolishness prevails, winds blow constantly in disorder.' Your Highness has shown signs of negligence in learning, and the portent of foolishness is answered by the wind itself. Does not Heaven's warning to you shine forth with unmistakable clarity?

    In ancient times, children entered the minor academy at eight and went forth to external teachers at ten. Yet the Duke of Xiang of Lu, though only six years old, attended the assemblies of the feudal lords—surely he did not always dine within the deep palace. Long ago, when the sage Cheng Zi served as Lecturer, he memorialized the throne saying: 'If a ruler spends little time with palace attendants and concubines, but much time in discourse with worthy gentlemen and great ministers, then naturally his vital essence transforms and his virtue becomes established.' Would that Your Highness, after greeting your mother each morning, would dine in the outer hall and summon the lecturers and scholars to attend constantly at your side, conversing gently and explaining principles from dusk until deep night. Let there be laid before you daily the mandate of Heaven and how it comes and goes, the inclination of human hearts and where they turn, the hardships of agriculture and the sufferings of soldiers, the roots of chaos and order, the traces of rise and fall, the rites and music of ancient and modern times, the worthiness or unworthiness of men and measures. When such instruction accumulates in the ruler's ear over time, understanding naturally matures, habit becomes nature, and you will share the virtue of Yao and Shun. How vastly greater is this than dwelling perpetually in the deep palace, corrupted by the deceit of women and attendants, becoming transformed from sage to fool!

    The casual disrespect of women and eunuchs is like tares that wound the sacred virtue; but the cultivation of worthy gentlemen and ministers is like rain and dew that nourish it. Let all palace women and inner servants be chosen according to the sage Cheng Zi's memorial—select those of forty or fifty years, grave and steady in bearing, to attend you, and allow none of tender years to approach, thus cutting off the root of private influence. As for all implements and articles you use, take as warning the ivory chopsticks and jade cups of the tyrant Zhou, and as model the humble garments of Yu the Great. Let no luxurious or showy objects appear before you; let no shallow or vulgar words reach your ears.

    The Director and Vice-Director of the Classics Lecture are as the Great Preceptor and Great Mentor of old; the Attendant Lecturers are as the Lesser Preceptor and Lesser Mentor. From this moment forward, when the Vice-Director enters the hall during your studies, rise up and yield your seat to receive instruction; when he departs, rise again to see him off. When the Attendant Lecturers come and go, likewise show them respect by yielding your seat and composing your countenance, thus demonstrating honor for your teachers. This is as when Tang made obeisance to Yi Yin before making him his minister—thus he ruled without toil; and as when Duke Huan bowed to Guan Zhong before making him his minister—thus he achieved dominance without strain. There is nothing more urgent for cultivating sacred virtue than this.

    I humbly beseech Your Highness to remember above the five-hundred-year legacy left by the Great Founder, and below the hopes of the countless multitudes of the Three Han. Do not condemn this lowly minister's earnest words, but receive and reflect upon them, thus opening the way to ten thousand years of great peace.
